  <div class="views-field-title">
                <span class="field-content"><a href="../library/testimony-deborah-seligsohn-4-4-11">Testimony by Deborah Seligsohn Before the Subcommittee on Energy and Power Committee on Energy and Commerce, April 4, 2011</a></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-image-fid">
                <span class="field-content"><img src="../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/debbi_testimony_4-8-11.jpg" alt="" title="" width="180" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/></span>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-field-library-file-fid">
                <div class="field-content"><div class="filefield-file"><img class="filefield-icon field-icon-application-pdf"  alt="application/pdf icon" src="../sites/all/modules/filefield/icons/application-pdf.png" /><a href="../files/chinainfo/seligsohn_testimony_4-4-11.pdf" type="application/pdf; length=92957">seligsohn_testimony_4-4-11.pdf</a></div></div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="views-field-teaser">
                <div class="field-content"><p>In my testimony today, I will start by discussing both where China is now and its plans for the upcoming five years, and then I will talk about some of the business opportunities this creates for other countries, including the United States, that want to compete in new energy technologies.</p></div>
  </div>
  </div>
